segments.text: Since I probably didn't answer many of them, which I apologize for, I really should know the history of the city better, but quite often what we wind up with in the planning is you're so busy trying to...

stay where you are that you don't have too much time to worry about the history and tradition uh galveston though does have a strong sense of history and i don't mean to imply people aren't aware of it the strand redevelopment uh venturi and rosh did a plan for it won a progressive architecture award while i was there using municipal data the only thing they added to the plan was
1975 was the award.
They did the work in 74.
The only thing they added to city data and design work that had been done to that point was that they came up with a color scheme and some sketches of what the street ought to look like.
But the city parking analysis, planning analysis, land use, everything, population, commercial opportunities, linkages, it had all been laid out by the city staff.
Which is typical of a lot of consultants, you know, and that's okay, it was a good plan.
They just put the spinach on it.
You know, they put the spinach on it and put it into a nice package so it looked good and tracked the attention.
They got their fee.
They got their fee and left town.
But, you know, that's alright, we need people like that, yes.
There's a historic district that has attracted a great deal of interest in the East End that has renovated what was really a decaying ghetto and slum to that point.
It became very popular.
While I was there, we established a second historic district called Central District that was kind of toward the seawall west of downtown.
Very fine old houses.
Marvelous.
It's one of the greatest collection of 19th century Victorian architecture that you'll find.
The Strand has got perhaps the greatest collection of commercial Victorian businesses that you'll find.
Cast iron storefronts bought to order from the east coast and bolted onto the building.
Instant architecture.
the best the world has to offer.
At that time.
At that time.
It was far more sophisticated than Houston.
Oh, yeah.
And the outcome, of course, was that you have a series of mansions in Galveston that even by today's standards are perhaps some of the greatest pieces of architecture that you can find.
And certain foremost examples, Bishop's Palace is a marvelous example.
Okay.
Let's go through the list here to see if there's anything we can pick up.
Well, do you know when the city first established the planning department as such?
Do you have any ideas?
I don't know when it was established, per se, as such.

I would say that if they had a planning commission established under the 61 charter, it would only be logical that a planning department to provide staff assistance to that commission would also have existed at that stage.
It's kind of an inescapable conclusion.
Now, it may have well been a city engineer or a planning inspector that was doing, or a department or building inspector doing the work, but I really don't know beyond that.
If they had a planning staff persuade before that, it would have somewhat surprised me.
Was there any relationship with citizen groups?
Oh geez.
A and B, what was the relationship between the planning department and the city council?
There was tremendous
relationships between citizens groups, extremely strong special interest groups in the community, neighborhood associations, historic associations, cultural societies,
Almost any three people that got together had a common ax to grind.
And part of it was the frustration of not having a city that was responsive.
You couldn't get the staff to answer a question.
You know, who put up the bicycle pathway signs?
And half the city staff would refuse to answer for fear they would get somebody in trouble.
And it turns out the guy wants to compliment the city on establishing a bicycle pathway, even though it may not be one of the most advanced designs.
You know, the more, here are some lines and markings, and let it go with that.
In many ways, the city staff reminisces very much about what it was like under the commissioner system, and you had to watch your step.
There was no civil service protection.
You made a mistake, you were canned immediately, and everything was political, and it was a very corrupt city.
It was wide open gambling, mafioso, and you'd wind up in the bay if you weren't careful.
And part of all of this was part of that 61 reform package to try to get some of that cleaned up.
And some of the mansions those people lived in are still there, you know, the criminal elements.
There's still a lot of gambling and prostitution.
I shouldn't say it, but I'm absolutely convinced the police department, many elements of the police department was still on the take when I was there.
Corruption in many aspects was pretty darn rampant, and it was kind of hard to get that image snapped out.
The citizens absolutely were adamant.
They were active.
There was good community organization.
We tended to support it because people that were active and citizens tended to support the kind of things that we thought needed to be done, too.
And I'll be honest with you, a lot of them were just absolute pains in terms of the planning staff and department.
They would pick us, you know, okay, you've got to put up with them for a while.
We would put up with them for a while.
They would call us and report things.
We'd be sitting there trying to ramp up a grant application for $500,000, and they're screaming because somebody's putting up a chain-link fence in a historic district without any building permits.
We'd have to drop that and try to get somebody out there to respond to it and red-tag it.
and catch the guy that's doing business, you know, and so forth.
And, you know, it's difficult working with people.

They don't understand all the time why you don't respond immediately or to their satisfaction, particularly when there's a conflicting interest, you know, and you're kind of caught in the middle and there's a judge saying, well, we know why you're seeing that, but we don't have any legal basis or authority to act.
So that's a problem.
The planning staff's relationship with the city council was interesting.
All city staffs would be drug into the city council chamber, particularly directors on occasion.
And it's a very complex thing in its personality more than anything else.
If the city council had respect for the staff and thought they were competent,
They would tend to listen and treat them as professionals.
They also tended to treat most of the staff as being incompetent and not being professionals.
The general feeling was, as left over from the commission days and the poor salaries, was that anybody that worked for Galveston obviously couldn't be that good.
If they were any good, they would be gone within a short time, so there was no real point in doing much more than using them to your maximum within the short term.
This is a common problem I think all cities have.
If you're really going to get it, why are we working for us?
And it permeates all levels of government.
So that's a real problem.
On the other hand, it's very obvious that they attract good attention and got things done and they notice things.
But there was a lot of reasons that they should think many of the city staff were incompetent, because in fact they were.
We had a city attorney, who I won't name now, who had come fresh out of law school and gotten a job as the third assistant city attorney, junior, bottom of the line.
And he kind of stayed there.
Well, of course, attorneys traditionally always get paid a little bit more, and that's the way they make connections within a community so they can go set up their own practice.
You know, you win your spurs and win a few cases and get a reputation, and you go from there.
Well, the outcome of all of that was that you're facing a situation where in most law schools, they don't teach much about municipal law.
They don't teach much about planning or land use law.
There's no money in it.
You know, why bother?
Nobody in his right mind is going to do that other than worrying about the bonds and the financial aspects.
Well, this guy, because he stayed there for a long period of time, kept getting promoted.
The guy above him quits and gets a good job, and he moves up.

Well, it got interesting because it got to the point that I was going downstairs, borrowing his law library, looking things up, and then carrying the open volumes into him to talk to him about what we were getting ready to do and why we could do it.
It also got to the point that
He would get put on the spot and make some very bad mistakes.
There's an incorporated village on Gallaston Island called Jamaica Beach.
It is there because he made a wrong decision on the spot in the city council chamber.
The mayor, who was a lawyer, said, are you sure you can do that?
And he said, well, yes, I'm convinced that if they want to withdraw their application that the clock would stop.
that doesn't necessarily hold so.

What they were saying is we would like more time to negotiate, and the clock on us incorporating within your extraterritorial jurisdiction certainly does not stop unless we efficiently remove the application.
So the result is Jamaica Beach is the only incorporated city on Galveston Island except Galveston.
The lawyer
was told by the mayor, are you absolutely sure?
You take all the time you want, because if you're wrong, it will be the last decision and advice you ever give to this council.
He's no longer there.
And it was deemed to be just a total disaster from the standpoint of the city.
And from a planning standpoint, it's utterly a disaster.
It's like creating a 450-unit subdivision in the middle of downtown Austin.
You know, with an independent police force on Tylan Park and University Park all over again, with totally incompetent and incapable of putting on a smaller schedule.
Yeah, on a smaller schedule.
Which makes it less viable.
Yeah.

And with all the same physical problems and constraints the city of Galveston as a whole had, but without any city staff or assistance or professional tax base to be able to do any work, which meant they tried to wing everything.
Oh, right.
How is the department itself organized?
Is there any specific formal organization in the planning department, would you say?
Oh, yeah.
Every bureaucracy has got to have a formal organization.
At the time I was there, it might almost be easier to sketch out
trying to explain it, but essentially.
We can do that after the interview.
Alright.
Have there been any fairs or expositions that you remember in or where I'm in Galveston that might have affected the planning?
I'm not sure.
Oh, like county fairs or trade expositions?
or major conventions or something like that?

Not that I know of, but let me say that Galveston historically was a resort city, and there were probably some things that happened prior to 1950 particularly that may have been very influential not only for Galveston, but the state as a whole.
Today, the convention center in Galveston is a very small, inadequate facility, simply based upon inadequate land capacity.
The hotel availability is quite limited.
I don't think you're going to see anything very large scale there, simply because of the lack of facility availability.
I'm sorry.
You're going.
Several things that I think we ought to touch on.
First of all,

This is well before you were there, of course, but you might have heard quite a bit about it, the Houston Ship Channel and the impact that had on the development of the island and also the railroad's impact on the development of the island.
Sure.
No problem at all.
Also, we just mentioned the fact that conventions were a problem for Galveston because of capacity for motel rooms and so forth.
I think I'd like to point out that another problem with Galveston in terms of conventions is that there is no airport servicing that is convenient for... Well, there is an airport in Galveston.
I know, but it's not convenient for convention areas.
Yeah.
I don't know what service they have in there now, but there was a subsidiary of...
One of the airlines was flying a commuter in, which they're flying to Havel and Otters, which maybe 10, 11 people.
That certainly is a problem.
Transportation into the city is a problem.
But that's almost an inevitable situation.
The railroads probably provided the ideal solution for the automobile in that it made it very accessible.
and that's one of the reasons it's such a popular recreational resort center.

The ship channel to Houston just absolutely devastated because there's simply no, you know, with the inadequate berthing space that was available in Galveston, the fact that it had just been devastated by a major storm, all combined to really, you know, create the demise of Galveston as the premier coastal city.
Land was much cheaper, much more abundantly available all along
the Ship Channel, Texas City, Port Arthur, all the way into the Ship Channel itself.
I don't think there's any doubt or argument about that.

And on the other hand, some people in Galveston would argue that was probably the best thing that ever happened, because otherwise Galveston would turn out to have looked like Texas City or the Houston Ship Channel.
And it certainly would have not been the more diverse cultured community that it is today.
So, you know, you can look at it as being something that was bad that happened from an economic sense, but on the other sense, it probably helped the community.
Okay, what about World Wars?
Galveston, in its strategic geographic position, had a pretty important role to play.
You may not be familiar with that, but I want to bring it up because there are military bases there yet.
During the Second World War, they had to fight .
Well, they had a coastal artillery position that was established there probably after the Civil War.
And so they had coastal artillery bunkers and Coast Guard usual activities like that.
At the present time they have major corps of engineers stationed there and they have Coast Guard stationed there probably equivalent of about two or three cutters and some smaller boats.
In terms of its strategic importance it's certainly not

of the levels say of Norfolk or San Diego or some of those places because you know it is removed it's not on the coast it's not where the action is but on the other hand certainly there was submarine activity in the gulf and Galveston and the city and
The refineries all provided critical resources, and from an economic sense and from basically kind of a submarine patrol sense, it was important.
But I don't think that it was as important from a national sense other than from the refinery and the materials and economic standpoint.
That's what made it so important.
No, there's none in Galveston, but it was kind of the port of entry for the refinery from Texas City and the ship channel and so forth.
Of course, that's where a lot of casualties came.
There were people being torpedoed out of the Houston Ship Channel and casualties would be picked up and brought into
UTMB, John Seeley, and it's probably why some of the Byrne interest and expertise was developed in the Shriners located at the Byrnes Institute there.
I think we've covered most of these questions already, the role of outside consultants and so forth.
Could you sum up what you think to be the current status of the planning in Galveston?
I would feel very comfortable surmising where they are at the present time.
And part of the reason being I've had so little direct contact with people there.
I would like to say one thing more about the consultants.
Galveston's been willing to spend money on consultants, which I think is a good thing.

The city staff there, like most communities, has really been too small, and in many cases it hasn't had expertise in particular things that need to be done, but they're not something you want somebody on staff with that expertise to kind of run out of.
You know, you do one building survey, and that's it.
You know, I mean, basically you've got the...
what is it, HABS, Historic American Building Survey, and the THC does everything.
So you get those two done, they mutually identify the community, and you don't need to have them back, hopefully, for another five or 10 years.
The same is true in terms of engineering expertise, transportation, traffic analysis.

A lot of times the community would have not been able to conduct its standard affairs and standard planning activities and made applications for some of these major grants without having a consultant hired.
Whether it's Bajar Johnson, Wilbur Smith we had working for us on the transit plan.
Bernard Johnson's done some things.
Martin Sprengler's done some things.
You know, we've had some firms that, you know, occasionally we snicker and laugh about because you pick up the plan and say, hey, this is just like the one Marvin did in Port Arthur and Beaumont.
You know, you see the same colors, the same press tape, you know, and the same format.
And you can tell which community spent more because there's more to the ones that spent more.
But in reality, those consultants are vital.
You cannot adequately do a good job without them.
And it would be expensive trying to keep those kind of people, those skills on staff year-round.
Okay.
Let's take a look at some of these influences on planning process in Galveston.
You talked about political influences.
What about religion?
Has religion played any, has it impacted the planning process at all?
If not, we just want to know.
I would say yes.
It's quite a Catholic.
It's very heavily Catholic.
There's a large Jewish population.
It's got an Eastern Orthodox Church.
As a matter of fact, it's a very Catholic community.
The Catholics have established an extensive parochial school system in the community.
At the time, there were something like four Catholic high schools operating at one point.
A lot of them have been consolidated and phased down to just junior high.
and so forth.
Interestingly enough, there's a very large black Catholic population in Galveston, which you don't find in most communities.
So it's not so much a matter of trying to maintain a segregated school system,
Religion does play a dominant role.
There's a lot of Catholic churches.
There's way too many for its population size and the number of Catholics.
Part of it was the historical development.
You get these older cities that develop in a very dense pattern.
People tend to walk or ride a carriage, and they don't go 5 and 10 miles to go to church.
But has religion had such impact in planning?
We're talking about religion here by itself, but has there been any causal relationship between the two?
I'm not sure what you mean by causal relationship.
I would say one thing, and that is, Bob, that what you've got is you have a lot of people of certain religious persuasions and categories that have informal and formal connections.
You get a city councilman that is Jewish or Methodist or whatever, he's going to have contacts because of that religious association.
And that creates a very kind of sophisticated social web and network that makes certain things a little bit more responsive or less possible than would have been otherwise.

The only building within the Central Historic District that was excluded from the historic district regulations, that is exempted, you know, you've got this one lot sitting there in the middle of the district, was the Jewish synagogue.
And part of it was because of these kinds of connections.
So yeah, there is some causal influence, but it's not that direct.
You know, it's not something like the Catholics are out to see a particular form of development or pattern occur.
As much as it is, it creates a social framework within which decisions are made and special considerations are taken of certain individuals.
Okay, very good.
Now, what about ethnic impacts on the planning process?
Oh, tremendous.
large Spanish population, large black population, virtually every country out of the Mediterranean you can name.
It's a coastal city, seaport, you've got lots of Portuguese, Spanish, Italians, Greeks, and these people in some cases have become very influential.
For example, dear old George Mitchell, A&M alumni, and it's Greek.
and he's had a tremendous impact on Galveston coastal development.
He's playing with the computer next door.
So, yeah, there's a lot of ethnic input.
Furthermore, the feds have mandated that minorities be taken into account and special consideration be given to the province.
Could you give us an example of how a particular ethnic group has impacted the planning process?
Basically, if you look at, say, the lower income groups that would need to be serviced and the way they're supposed to spend money.
You're loud today, Wayne.
Yes.
And so the outcome is that the way physical developments are funded through, say, community development block grants, the way bus routes are laid out, the way
decisions are made about which school to close or not to close or renovate, all tend to be considered in terms of their impact on various ethnic and racial groups.
It's a factor within the decision and planning process.
And if it is not clearly reflected in terms of the outcome, you're endangering a lot of your funding processes.
And that's something that when I was there, we were very concerned about.
We made decisions.
based upon how things were going to look to federal reviewing agencies or to courts if we got drug into court.
Okay, very good.
I think that covers it very well.
The next impact, of course, is geographic.
And that one could say a lot about, to be honest, this geographic impact on the planning process.
Well, let's just start back in 1830-something.

If you look at the population growth of the city of Galveston from the state of Texas, Republic of Texas, when it was first being founded, people tended to migrate in from Arkansas and Louisiana from the east.
The frontier at the time of the founding of the Republic was Austin.
We still had Indian massacres occurring right out here at Barton Springs.
1836, 1840, occasionally have Cheyenne War Party penetrate into
down below San Marcos and right into East Texas before they were being chased out.

So the whole population movement of the state was essentially from the east, and this immediately said, okay, what is the transportation route that you are logically going to try to find in terms of bringing goods and commodities in?
Well, it so happened, technologically, there was no decent way of moving anything
except by water, particularly bulk commodities and cargoes.
Man, it was slow and hard going to try to have any kind of cart or wagon.
There were no roads.
And so immediately you begin to look at the coast in terms of potential river relationships and navigation.
Now, it so happened the only decent natural harbor in the state of Texas is Galveston.
It is the only one.
Every other one has got serious swamps.
There's a lot wrong with Galveston.
But it's better than anything else on this side of New Orleans, going all the way down through Mexico.
There are problems with Corpus and Brownsville, which are the only other two natural decent harbors on the coast.
Specifically, what are they going to service?
Nothing.
And Alveston tended to have good river relationships.
He could go up the Trinity, he could go down to the end of the island, go up the Brazos, and he'd get all the way to Waco on occasion.
Jerusalem on the Brazos, right.
The outcome is that Galveston became the natural economic center of Port City simply because of its transportation relationships.
Traditionally, the limit to navigation on the Brazos most of the year was Millikan.
Y'all remember Millikan?
You heard this story before?
Okay.

um and so Galveston became the premier city because this is where all the change of commodities and transportation techniques river boats to oceans schooners to and then when the railroad got built they were building the railroad that got as far as Milken they stopped building it because in 1961 the civil war happened they couldn't get any steel for rails well Milken
Anyway, so the outcome was they got as far as Milliken, and that's where the change in transportation again occurred, you know, back over to ox carts and wagons.
So basically all of the commerce of the inland area and developed area of Texas for years and years came through Galveston.
The railroads tended to reinforce that pattern.
Water relationships reinforced that pattern, all because of the natural harbor.
Now there was a sandbar out there, but still it was the smallest sandbar that you could find on any of these rivers, because this was the largest flow coming in.

So the geographic pattern was, gee, you come around, you go to the backside of the island, nice and smooth, you drive a few piers in, you have the Strand, which is in fact a commercial street, and the back of all those stores are warehouses, and all kinds of wonderful things happen economically.
That's the reason Galveston was there, and that's the reason it was developed.

And when technology changed that pattern, you know, we got a new ship channel, and we became a little bit less rail dependent, and the population shift kind of moved around, Galveston began to lose itself, particularly because of its rather hazardous exposed position to the Gulf in terms of storms.
The natural elevation of Galveston Island is about 12 to 14 foot.
The 100-year flood elevation is 12 feet.
The island will go completely underwater.
In response to that, they built the seawall.
The seawall will probably fail someday.

works so far but the way the seawall works is that it keeps the waves running through the island destroying buildings and all the water seeps around the seawall and backs in from the bay and puts all the entire island under water except for the top of the seawall well but that way all you have is wind you don't have the destructive force of the waves which is tremendous in terms of energy levels
And all of your buildings tend to be built up on pilings, pretty much.

Almost every building in town, you either walk up to get in, or it's built up on telephone poles with the hope that the water gets underneath and damages the garage and the car, but at least it doesn't wipe out your building.
Have there been any minimum elevation requirements for construction caused by geographic factors?
The city adopted a 10-foot elevation requirement, and I can't remember the exact history on it now at one point, for residential purposes only.
This was, I think, a response to the 161 storm.
